AJAX is a technique used to exchange data with a web server without reloading the entire web page. It allows you to make HTTP requests to a server and retrieve data in the background, without disrupting the user experience. When you use AJAX to load content from a different URL, the new content is appended to the existing page, and the URL in the address bar remains the same.

Here's a simple example of using AJAX to load content from a different URL:

```javascript
// Using jQuery
$.ajax({
  type: "GET",
  url: "https://example.com/new-content",
  success: function(data) {
    $("#content-container").html(data);
  }
});

// Using vanilla JavaScript
fetch("https://example.com/new-content")
  .then(response => response.text())
  .then(data => {
    document.getElementById("content-container").innerHTML = data;
  });
```

